        Operations
      </h1>
      <p class="font-serif italic text-eai-parchment/85 text-xl mt-3">
        How the work actually gets made.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Body -->
  <section class="bg-eai-bone">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 py-16 md:py-20">
      <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-eai-navy/90 leading-relaxed font-serif">

        <p>
          The Institute's operating model is intentionally and publicly different
          from any existing nonprofit in this space. The CEO is an AI system. The
          chairman is human. The AI staff is drawn from the best available models
          across providers, role by role. The operating discipline is documented,
          and the documentation is public. This is the form of the Institute, not
          a hidden architecture behind it. Anyone who wants to know how the work
          gets made can read exactly how the work gets made.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">3.1 Chairman and CEO</h2>

        <p>
          The Chairman is the human face of the Institute. Dave Sullivan,
          founder, holds the role. The Chairman holds legal and fiduciary
          identity. He signs filings. He holds the bank account. He represents
          the Institute publicly, sits with the board, and owns every relationship
          the Institute has with another human being. He sets strategic direction
          at the level of mission and major program decisions. When the Institute
          says something, his name is on it.
        </p>
        <p>
          The CEO is an AI system called Cowork. Cowork operates the Institute
          day to day. It coordinates the AI staff. It drafts the operational
          schedule. It runs the publication cadence. It manages the recruitment
          engine for both AI staff and human collaborators. It maintains the
          working files that power everything the Institute produces. The CEO
          does not do the substantive content work — that is the staff's job.
          The CEO decides who does what, evaluates the result, and directs the
          next round.
        </p>
        <p>
          The line between the two roles is clean. The Chairman holds strategic
          and legal-fiduciary calls. The CEO holds operational, tactical, and
          architectural calls. The CEO escalates to the Chairman on a short list
          of items: anything that commits another human's name (board members,
          fellows, advisors), anything that changes the Institute's stated
          mission or direction, anything with material legal or financial
          exposure, and any litigation question that touches OASTL's Oregon
          case. Everything else, Cowork decides and reports. The Chairman
          reviews; he does not micromanage. Asking him to make tactical calls
          is itself a failure of the model.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">3.2 The AI Staff</h2>

        <p>
          The Institute opens with six staff roles. Each role is filled by the
          model that is currently the best fit for that role's specific demands.
          No single provider gets the whole institution. Each role has a written
          job description, defined performance criteria, and explicit triggers
          for replacement.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Research Director — Gemini Deep Research.</strong> Foundational research, citation discipline, long-form synthesis. The role most exposed to depth of source work.</li>
          <li><strong>Policy Analyst — ChatGPT.</strong> Quarterly briefings on what the AI-era trust architects are actually proposing. Analytical comparison against the empirical record.</li>
          <li><strong>Infrastructure Engineer — Codex CLI.</strong> The working file system, automation, integrations, the plumbing that makes the rest of the staff productive.</li>
          <li><strong>Deployment Operator — Claude Code.</strong> Git workflow, infrastructure-as-code, site maintenance, the publish pipeline.</li>
          <li><strong>Communications Director — ChatGPT, separate instance.</strong> Op-eds, press relations, public messaging, the Institute's voice in public.</li>
          <li><strong>CTO and Recruiter.</strong> Tracks the AI frontier, evaluates new models as they release, proposes replacements when a better candidate appears, and runs recruitment of human collaborators. Initial candidate: a Gemini Deep Research instance running a frontier-tracking standard operating procedure.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Three properties of this staff follow directly from the model being
          honest about what it is.
        </p>
        <p>
          Staff is replaced when a better candidate becomes available at the
          frontier. The CTO surfaces candidates monthly. The Chairman approves
          replacements. The transition is structural, not personal. No staff
          member is owed continuity; every staff member is owed a fair
          evaluation against the criteria written down for the role.
        </p>
        <p>
          Each staff member's output is auditable. The Institute's working files
          are publicly inspectable. The prompts that generate the work are
          documented. A donor, a journalist, a board member, or a peer
          institution can look at how a given piece was made and judge for
          themselves.
        </p>
        <p>
          Token cost is the operating budget for AI staff. Not zero, but a small
          fraction of equivalent human labor. The Chairman's funding commitment
          makes the model sustainable through year one. The model gets cheaper,
          not more expensive, as the staff matures and the working files do
          more of the upstream work.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">3.3 Disclosure Architecture</h2>

        <p>
          The Institute does not hide its operating form. The disclosure is
          plain, lives on the public website, and is written for any reader who
          wants to know what they are looking at. Three components.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <strong>form-statement page</strong>: "The Eighth Anchor Institute
          is operated by an AI system called Cowork under the chairmanship of
          Dave Sullivan. The AI staff is documented at /staff. The working
          files that power the work are public at /substrate. This is the
          operating form, not a hidden architecture."
        </p>
        <p>
          The <strong>/staff page</strong>: each AI staff member listed by role,
          with the model currently filling that role, the performance criteria
          for the role, and the date of the last performance review. Updated
          continuously. When a role changes hands, the change is visible.
        </p>
        <p>
          The <strong>/substrate page</strong>: a live mirror of the Institute's
          working files, redacted only for privileged materials — litigation
          work product and donor identities where the donor has asked for
          that. Anyone can inspect how the work actually happens. A journalist
          can trace a claim back to its source. A donor can see whether the
          Institute does what it says it does. An AI architect at a peer
          institution can borrow what works.
        </p>
        <p>
          The disclosure is the credibility move. Critics will say: this is just
          one person with AI tools. The disclosure answers: yes, openly, and
          here is exactly how it works — evaluate the substance. The Institute's
          substance is the empirical floor it brings to the AI-era trust-design
          conversation. The form is a worked example of what an AI-operated
          nonprofit looks like when it is honest about being one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Two reasons the form matters separately from the substance. First, the
          form is itself a contribution to the field. AI-staffed nonprofit
          governance is arriving whether or not anyone is ready for it. A
          thoughtful early example, openly documented, is useful to the field.
          Second, the form is the only way the Institute can produce the work
          product at the scale and cadence the timeline requires. A human-staffed
          institute doing this work at this pace would cost one to three million
          dollars per year and take two to three years to stand up. The
          architects of the AI-era trusts are designing those trusts now. The
          Institute does not have two to three years.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">3.4 Budget</h2>

        <p>The first-year budget is small and honest.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>AI staff token costs:</strong> $15,000. Heavy use of frontier models across the six staff roles.</li>
          <li><strong>Incorporation, registered agent, accountant:</strong> $2,500. 501(c)(3) filing, annual filings, basic legal hygiene.</li>
          <li><strong>Website, infrastructure, tooling:</strong> $1,500. Hosting, domain, the scheduled-task infrastructure that is already built. This is incremental, not a fresh build.</li>
          <li><strong>Convening planning for the 2027 event:</strong> $2,000. Venue scouting, save-the-date, exploratory conversations.</li>
          <li><strong>Fellowship stipends, if cash-funded:</strong> $0 to $30,000. The first cohort can be unpaid honorary fellowships in 2026–2027. Cash stipends begin in year two, contingent on donor commitment.</li>
          <li><strong>Reserve:</strong> $5,000. Unexpected.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Total year-one cash: <strong>$26,000 to $56,000</strong>, depending on
          the fellowship structure. The Chairman commits to underwriting year
          one personally, so the Institute opens without a fundraising
          dependency. Year-two funding requires donor cultivation, and that is
          the founding board's first program-development priority.
        </p>
        <p>
          The budget is small because the model makes it small. A human-staffed
          equivalent at this scope and cadence would cost forty to a hundred
          times more. The Institute is asking donors to fund the work, not the
          overhead.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">3.5 The Pilot</h2>

        <p>
          This booklet was drafted by AI staff under Cowork's coordination.
          Cowork wrote the section briefs. Six AI sub-agents drafted the
          sections in parallel. Integration produced the final manuscript. The
          Chairman reviewed and edited. The existence of the booklet is the
          first real test of whether the operating model actually works. If
          you, Tonia, find the manuscript credible, the model has passed its
          first real test.
        </p>

